<subSubSection id="A58C8EA1F32EFFA8E29475143268F93E" pageId="6" pageNumber="72" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="ED29DD2AF32EFFA8E29475143268F93E" blockId="6.[189,798,1723,1926]" lastBlockId="6.[835,1443,1461,1912]" pageId="6" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="DFE20138F32EFFA8E2947514370AF89A" bold="true" box="[189,328,1866,1890]" pageId="6" pageNumber="72">Comments.</emphasis>
This species was recently recorded by 
<bibRefCitation id="8907A0DBF32EFFA8E294753037C0F87E" author="Stark, B. P. &amp; B. C. Kondratieff &amp; B. Gill" box="[189,386,1902,1926]" pageId="6" pageNumber="72" pagination="78 - 93" refId="ref6905" refString="Stark, B. P., B. C. Kondratieff, &amp; B. Gill. 2012. New species and records of Anacroneuria (Plecoptera: Perlidae) from Ecuador and Paraguay. Illiesia, 8: 78 - 93." type="journal article" year="2012">Stark et al. (2012)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<specimenCount id="FB9016A3F32EFFA8E3EF75303470F87E" box="[454,562,1902,1926]" pageId="6" pageNumber="72" type="male">two male</specimenCount>
specimens collected together with the additional males (listed above) and first female specimen recorded here and described below. The adult head and pronotum are also illustrated for the first time (
<figureCitation id="75ADC1AFF32EFFA8E680747E32B3F9C0" box="[1193,1265,1568,1592]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[189,241,1319,1343]" captionTargetBox="[385,1303,300,1240]" captionTargetId="figure-295@6.[328,1303,257,1240]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 6-11. Anacroneuria female structures. (6-8 = A. carchi). 6. Head and pronotum. 7. Outline of egg. 8. Subgenital plate. (9-11 = A. cruza). 9. Head and pronotum. 10. Outline of egg. 11. Subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4752753" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4752753/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="72">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). The Rio Lita collection site is located in the Northwestern Ecuadorian Pacific Zone, which forms part of the 
<collectingRegion id="2F5213C8F32EFFA8E16A74D435CCF95A" box="[835,910,1674,1698]" country="Colombia" name="Choco" pageId="6" pageNumber="72">Choco</collectingRegion>
Biogeographic Region, an area known for its hot, humid climate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A58C8EA1F32EFFA9E16A748F3699FEA5" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="6" pageNumber="72" type="description">
<paragraph id="ED29DD2AF32EFFA8E16A748F33E1F88F" blockId="6.[835,1443,1461,1912]" pageId="6" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="DFE20138F32EFFA8E16A748F35E3F911" bold="true" box="[835,929,1745,1769]" pageId="6" pageNumber="72">Female.</emphasis>
Forewing length 
<quantity id="2A6E70CFF32EFFA8E655748F3291F911" box="[1148,1235,1745,1769]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="72" unit="mm" value="17.0">17 mm</quantity>
. Subgenital plate pale, hairy and bilobed, mesal notch relatively narrow and shallow (
<figureCitation id="75ADC1AFF32EFFA8E679754732DAF8C9" box="[1104,1176,1817,1841]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[189,241,1319,1343]" captionTargetBox="[385,1303,300,1240]" captionTargetId="figure-295@6.[328,1303,257,1240]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 6-11. Anacroneuria female structures. (6-8 = A. carchi). 6. Head and pronotum. 7. Outline of egg. 8. Subgenital plate. (9-11 = A. cruza). 9. Head and pronotum. 10. Outline of egg. 11. Subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4752753" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4752753/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="72">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Posterior transverse sclerite on sternum 9 pale, mesal field of sternum 9 uniformly covered with moderately long pale setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ED29DD2AF32FFFA9E29472A33699FEA5" blockId="7.[189,797,253,349]" pageId="7" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="DFE20138F32FFFA9E29472A336B1FEED" bold="true" box="[189,243,253,277]" pageId="7" pageNumber="73">Egg.</emphasis>
Length ca. 
<quantity id="2A6E70CFF32FFFA9E3A172A337B4FEED" box="[392,502,253,277]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="7" pageNumber="73" unit="mm" value="0.32">0.32 mm</quantity>
, greatest width ca. 
